## 🗄️ Database Layer

### ✅ Good
- Interface-driven design (`db.DB`) is excellent.
- WAL mode + connection pool config on SQLite is correct.
- `EnsureSchema` with `sync.Once` prevents repeated migrations on every API call.

### 🔴 Critical — Duplicate Implementations
`sqlite.go` is **1,871 lines** and `postgres.go` is **62 kB**. These two files implement
the same interface with near-identical logic (just different SQL dialects). ~70% of the code
is duplicated.

**Fix:** Extract shared query-building logic into a `internal/db/base.go` that both
implementations compose. Use `sqlx` or a minimal query helper to reduce repetition.

### 🟡 Medium — No Query Parameterisation Audit
A quick grep shows some dynamic string concatenation in list queries. All user-supplied values
(domain names, search strings) must go through parameterised queries. Do a security audit of
every place you build a SQL string.

### 🟡 Medium — `GlobalSubdomain` exposes raw DB struct to HTTP
`db.GlobalSubdomain` is serialised directly in API responses. You should have a separate
DTO/response struct in the API layer so DB schema changes don't silently change the API
contract.

