## 🎨 UI / CSS

### ✅ Strengths
- **Excellent design system** — CSS custom properties for all colours, spacing, and
  transitions is exactly right.
- **Responsive sidebar** with metrics bar and connection status — polished.
- **Premium dark theme** — glassmorphism cards, gradient accents, micro-animations (hover
  lift, badge pulse) are well done.
- **JetBrains Mono** for code/domain names is a great choice.
- Sticky table headers, smooth skeleton loaders, badge system all look great.

### 🟡 Medium — No Responsive/Mobile Layout
The sidebar is fixed-width with no collapse mechanism. On viewports under 900px the layout
breaks. While this is a dashboard (mostly desktop), adding a hamburger-collapse sidebar would
make it usable on laptops and tablets.

```css
@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .sidebar { width: 60px; }
  .sidebar .nav-item span:not(.nav-icon) { display: none; }
  .logo-text, .logo-version { display: none; }
}
```

### 🟡 Medium — `styles.css` is 3,598 Lines — No Organization
The CSS file is a single flat file with no section demarcation beyond comments.

**Recommendation (for a no-build setup, just split files):**
```
styles/
  base.css        → reset, typography, scrollbar
  layout.css      → shell, sidebar, topbar, content
  components.css  → cards, badges, tables, buttons
  scan.css        → scan detail, phase progress
  r2.css          → R2 browser
  auth.css        → login gate
  animations.css  → keyframes
  premium.css     → glassmorphism, glow effects
```

### 🟡 Medium — Emoji Icons vs. SVG Icons
Navigation uses emoji (⚡📡🌐🔗👁️🎯🔑🤖🍏⚙️) which render inconsistently across
OS/browser and don't scale cleanly. Replace with a small SVG icon set (e.g. Lucide, which
is < 2 kB tree-shaken).

### 🟢 Low — `version` is Hardcoded in HTML
```html
<div class="logo-version">v4.1.0</div>
```
This should be injected at build time or fetched from `/api/version` on load.

### 🟢 Low — No Loading Indicator for Initial Bootstrap
On first load, there's no global loading spinner before modules initialise. Users see blank
areas until the JS poll completes. A CSS-only skeleton that's visible before JS runs would
improve perceived performance.

